<dl id="n40079d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40079d">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40079d"> 79(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> soft anvil</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The erotic Book of Exposition in the Science of Coition]</font> begins with exclaiming &ldquo;Alhamdolillah &mdash; Laud to the Lord who adorned the virginal bosom with breasts and who made the thighs of women anvils for the spear-handles of men!&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 200</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cf. N43 (VI.B.35):016: blacksmith marriage anvil. <br>Cf. <cite>FW</cite> 197.11: Who blocksmitt her saft anvil [a late addition to I.8]. <br>Cf. <cite>FW</cite> 194.15: tree of the knowledge of beautiful andevil </mm> </dd></dl>
